	 When an&nbsp;egg is&nbsp;forming, it&nbsp;develops a&nbsp;protective protein shell, which functions are very important:
</p>
<ul>
	<li>recognition of&nbsp;sperm of&nbsp;one’s own species of&nbsp;mammals;</li>
	<li>cell integrity preservation;</li>
	<li>defense from penetration of&nbsp;microorganisms, mutagens, harmful agents and more than one spermatozoa;</li>
	<li>egg protection during its travel inside the fallopian tube;</li>
	<li>keeping dividing cells together.</li>
</ul>
<p>
	 On&nbsp;day 5&nbsp;after fertilization, all functions of&nbsp;the protective shell are completed, so&nbsp;it&nbsp;must get thinner and degenerate so&nbsp;that the embryo can get out and attach to&nbsp;the uterine wall. However, it&nbsp;was found that in&nbsp;IVF cycles quite often the protective shell does not degenerate, which prevents implantation.
